The paper discusses a consensus framework that is able to switch consensus protocols at run-time, which is a topic related to distributed computing (cs.DC). The paper also discusses the effectiveness of the proposed framework in terms of security and performance, which is related to computer security and cryptography (cs.CR). The framework involves the use of various consensus protocols, which is related to data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The framework is designed to adapt to changing workload conditions, which is related to control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the framework involves communication and networking, which is related to networking and internet architecture (cs.NI).
